### üåê **What is Lifecycle Management?**

**Lifecycle Management** in Azure automatically **moves or deletes data** based on **rules** and **time**.
It helps you **save money** and **manage storage efficiently**.

### üí° **Why use Lifecycle Management?**

* To **reduce cost** (move old data to cheaper tiers).
* To **automate data movement** (no manual work).
* To **delete unused or expired data** automatically.

### üïí **When to use it**

* When data becomes **old or rarely accessed**.
* When you want to **move data** from **Hot ‚Üí Cool ‚Üí Archive** automatically.
* When you want to **delete files** after a certain number of days.


### ‚öôÔ∏è **How it works (Simple Example):**

| Rule           | Action                            |
| -------------- | --------------------------------- |
| After 30 days  | Move from **Hot ‚Üí Cool** tier     |
| After 90 days  | Move from **Cool ‚Üí Archive** tier |
| After 365 days | **Delete** the blob automatically |

### üß† **Simple Line to Remember:**
> Lifecycle Management = **Automatic data movement and deletion to save cost over time.**




‚öôÔ∏è What is IOPS?
------------------------------
IOPS means Input/Output Operations Per Second.
It measures how fast a storage device (like SSD or disk) can read and write data.

üí° Why IOPS is Important
It shows performance of storage.
Higher IOPS = faster data access.
Important for databases, VMs, and applications that need quick response.

üïí When to Use or Check IOPS
When you need high-speed storage (for example, running SQL Server, SAP, or virtual machines).
When you compare SSD vs HDD performance.
When you choose Azure Disk types (Standard HDD, Standard SSD, Premium SSD, Ultra Disk ‚Äî each gives different IOPS).


