### üåê **What is Azure Storage Explorer?**
------------------------------------------------------
**Azure Storage Explorer** is a **free desktop tool** from Microsoft that helps you **view, upload, download, and manage** your Azure Storage data easily.

### üí° **Why use Azure Storage Explorer?**

* To **access Azure Storage without using the Azure Portal**.
* To **manage blobs, files, queues, and tables** visually.
* To **upload, download, rename, or delete** files easily.
* To **connect multiple storage accounts** in one place.

### ‚öôÔ∏è **When to use it**

* When you want to **work with Azure Storage directly from your computer**.
* When you need to **transfer data** (upload or download large files).
* When developers or admins want **offline access** to manage storage.

### üßæ **Main Features:**

| Feature                                 | Description                               |
| --------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **Blob Storage**                        | Upload, download, view, and delete blobs. |
| **File Shares**                         | Access shared folders like normal files.  |
| **Queues**                              | Manage and monitor message queues.        |
| **Tables**                              | View and edit table data.                 |
| **Connect via SAS / Connection String** | Securely connect to any storage account.  |

---

### üíª **Simple Line to Remember:**

> **Azure Storage Explorer = Easy desktop tool to manage Azure Storage without the portal.**


Perfect üëç Here‚Äôs a **step-by-step procedure** to connect **Azure Storage Explorer** to your **Azure Storage Account** üëá
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## üß≠ **Step-by-Step: Connect Azure Storage Explorer**

### ü™ü **Step 1: Download and Install**

1. Go to üëâ [https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/features/storage-explorer/](https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/features/storage-explorer/)
2. Download the version for your system (**Windows, macOS, or Linux**).
3. Install and open **Azure Storage Explorer** on your computer.
---
### üîê **Step 2: Open Connection Panel**
1. When it opens, click **‚ÄúAdd Account‚Äù** or the **plug icon** üîå (left toolbar).
2. You will see different connection options.
---
### üß© **Step 3: Choose How to Connect**
You can connect in **3 main ways** üëá

#### ‚úÖ **Option 1: Sign in to Azure**

* Choose **‚ÄúAdd an Azure Account‚Äù**.
* Sign in using your **Azure credentials (email & password)**.
* It will automatically show all **your storage accounts** in the explorer.
---
#### ‚úÖ **Option 2: Use Connection String**

* In Azure Portal ‚Üí Go to your **Storage Account** ‚Üí **Access Keys**.
* Copy the **Connection String**.
* In Storage Explorer ‚Üí Choose **‚ÄúUse a Connection String‚Äù** ‚Üí Paste it ‚Üí Click **Connect**.
---
#### ‚úÖ **Option 3: Use SAS Token**

* In Azure Portal ‚Üí Storage Account ‚Üí **Shared access signature (SAS)**.
* Generate SAS Token and copy the URL.
* In Storage Explorer ‚Üí Choose **‚ÄúUse a SAS URI‚Äù** ‚Üí Paste the full SAS URL ‚Üí Click **Connect**.
---
### üìÅ **Step 4: Explore Your Storage**
After connection, you can now:
* Open **Blob Containers**, **File Shares**, **Queues**, and **Tables**.
* **Upload / Download files** easily.
* **Rename, delete, or view properties** of files

---

## üîë **1. Access Keys**
-----------------------------------------
### üí° What it is:
A **master key** (like a password) that gives **full access** to your entire Azure Storage Account.

### ‚öôÔ∏è Used for:
* Connecting **apps or tools** like Azure Storage Explorer.
* Accessing **all containers, files, queues, and tables**.

### ‚ö†Ô∏è Risk:
* If someone gets your access key ‚Üí they can **control everything** in your storage account.
* You must **keep it secret** and **rotate (regenerate)** it regularly.

---

## üïì **2. SAS Token (Shared Access Signature)**
--------------------------------------------------------
### üí° What it is:
A **temporary and limited access link**.
You can give **specific permission** (read, write, delete, etc.) for a **specific time** to a **specific resource**.

### ‚öôÔ∏è Used for:
* Sharing files safely.
* Giving access to **one blob or container** only.
* Allowing users to access data **without giving full account control**.

### ‚úÖ Example:
You can give someone a SAS token that allows:
* Only **read** access
* To **one container**
* For **24 hours**

---
## üìä **Comparison Table:**

| Feature          | Access Key                            | SAS Token                                  |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| **Access Level** | Full access to entire storage account | Limited access (specific resource)         |
| **Security**     | High risk if leaked                   | Safer ‚Äî expires automatically              |
| **Time Limit**   | No (permanent until regenerated)      | Yes (you can set expiry time)              |
| **Permissions**  | All (read, write, delete, list, etc.) | Customizable (only what you allow)         |
| **Best For**     | Admins or apps that need full access  | Sharing or temporary access to users/files |

---
### üß† **Simple Lines to Remember:**

> **Access Key = Full control (like admin password)**
> **SAS Token = Limited, timed access (like a temporary pass)**



MIGRATION::::::::::::
-------------------------------
* migrate the data from onprime to azure storage we have multiple options are there:::
1) if the size of the data is less like 1gb,2gb,etc using storage exploror,AZ copy,azure cli,azure powershell, this is online migration.
2) if the size of the data is morte like 1TB,50TB,etc using import/export job,azure data box,this is ofline data transfer.

| Aspect    | Online Migration                | Offline Migration                             |
| --------- | ------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Data Size | Small ‚Üí Medium (up to ~50 TB)   | Large (50 TB ‚Üí Petabytes)                     |
| Speed     | Depends on internet             | Faster for huge data, independent of internet |
| Tool      | AzCopy, Data Factory, File Sync | Azure Data Box                                |
| Cost      | Only bandwidth                  | Cost of Data Box + shipping                   |
| Security  | SAS / Keys over network         | Encrypted appliance                           |


## **1Ô∏è‚É£ Online Migration Scenario (Over Network)**
**Use this when:**
* Data size is **small to medium** (up to ~50 TB, depending on bandwidth).
* **High-speed internet** is available (100 Mbps+).
* You need **frequent or incremental uploads**.
* You want **faster setup** without waiting for hardware delivery.
* Examples:
  * Migrating **5 TB of file shares** from an on-premises server to Azure Blob Storage using **AzCopy**.
  * Moving **databases** with minimal downtime using **Azure Database Migration Service**.
  * Syncing **active project files** using **Azure File Sync** for hybrid storage.

‚úÖ **Advantages:** Quick setup, no shipping delays, good for incremental sync.
‚ö†Ô∏è **Limitations:** Large data over slow internet can take weeks; bandwidth cost may be high.

---

## **2Ô∏è‚É£ Offline Migration Scenario (Using Data Box / Data Box Heavy)**
**Use this when:**
* Data size is **very large** (50 TB ‚Üí Petabytes).
* Internet is **slow or unreliable**.
* You want **secure bulk transfer** without stressing network.
* Examples:
  * Moving **120 TB of backups** or archive data to Azure.
  * Migrating **VM images, large media libraries, or logs** from multiple sites.
  * One-time bulk migration for **data centers or branch offices**.

‚úÖ **Advantages:** Faster for huge data, secure, avoids long internet transfer times.
‚ö†Ô∏è **Limitations:** Requires ordering hardware, shipping time, and additional cost for device.


üí° **Simple Line to Remember:**

> **Online = small/medium data + fast internet**
> **Offline = huge data or slow internet**





